WEBVTT

00:03.100 --> 00:04.566
Friends.

00:04.566 --> 00:06.133
They're the people
who get you,

00:06.133 --> 00:07.233
support you,

00:07.233 --> 00:10.000
understand you in ways
that others just don't.

00:10.000 --> 00:12.300
They're the people
you share your life with,

00:12.300 --> 00:15.300
but what happens when
your life starts to change?

00:15.300 --> 00:16.600
Oh, hey.

00:16.600 --> 00:17.433
Whoa, hey.

00:17.433 --> 00:18.466
Come on, one piece.

00:18.466 --> 00:21.000
I've got a six hour drive
ahead of me.

00:21.000 --> 00:22.233
That bacon is for Judith.

00:22.233 --> 00:25.000
Please, I am starving.

00:25.000 --> 00:27.000
(chuckles)
Don't guilt me out.

00:27.000 --> 00:29.233
You're the one who's
abandoning me for the weekend.

00:29.233 --> 00:30.566
It's my cousin's stag.

00:30.566 --> 00:32.166
Fine, one piece.

00:32.166 --> 00:34.033
But don't eat it all
'cause Judith loves bacon.

00:34.033 --> 00:35.166
And scones.

00:35.166 --> 00:36.366
Wow, you're really
going all out.

00:36.366 --> 00:37.233
Yeah...

00:37.233 --> 00:38.333
I'm kind of anxious.

00:38.333 --> 00:40.333
Brunch with your best friend
makes you anxious?

00:40.333 --> 00:43.100
Well, I can't even remember
the last time we hung out.

00:43.100 --> 00:45.700
I mean, we used to see
each other all the time,

00:45.700 --> 00:47.333
talk every day,

00:47.333 --> 00:48.733
but now it's like...

00:48.733 --> 00:50.133
She kinda has a newborn.

00:50.133 --> 00:51.700
I know, but I swear,

00:51.700 --> 00:53.266
every time we make plans,
she cancels.

00:53.266 --> 00:54.666
Well, when Michael had kids,

00:54.666 --> 00:57.200
we went from drinking buddies
to playground patrol.

00:57.200 --> 00:58.200
But you stayed friends.

00:58.200 --> 00:59.200
Sure,
with a few adjustments.

00:59.200 --> 01:00.400
Oh.

01:02.233 --> 01:03.500
(telephone rings)

01:03.500 --> 01:05.033
Why is she calling
from home?

01:05.033 --> 01:06.033
(phone rings)

01:07.100 --> 01:08.366
Hello!

01:08.366 --> 01:10.500
Explain to me why
we're not born with teeth.

01:10.500 --> 01:12.500
I'm gonna go
out on a limb here

01:12.500 --> 01:13.666
and say breast-feeding?

01:13.666 --> 01:16.433
Three hours of sleep,
Erica.

01:16.433 --> 01:17.433
Oh, Jude.

01:18.700 --> 01:21.133
So, I guess that means
we're not--

01:21.133 --> 01:25.500
No, no, I promised myself
I wouldn't cancel, but--

01:25.500 --> 01:27.100
Can we meet up
a little later?

01:27.100 --> 01:29.266
Like at 2 o'clock?

01:29.266 --> 01:31.066
I-I've got baby yoga
this afternoon

01:31.066 --> 01:32.633
near that goblins place
you like.

01:32.633 --> 01:34.266
Not a problem at all.

01:34.266 --> 01:36.200
I will see you then.

01:36.200 --> 01:37.166
(phone beeps off)

01:38.200 --> 01:39.666
Hey, you all right?

01:41.133 --> 01:44.166
For your trip to Montreal,

01:44.166 --> 01:46.466
I give you five scones
and a pound of bacon.

01:46.466 --> 01:48.300
(chuckles)

01:48.300 --> 01:49.700
(passionate kissing)

01:56.700 --> 02:00.333
Hey.

02:00.333 --> 02:02.566
Oh, it's the incredible
growing baby.

02:02.566 --> 02:03.566
Hi.

02:03.566 --> 02:05.266
Oh.

02:05.266 --> 02:07.633
When have we ever gone this
long without hanging out?

02:07.633 --> 02:08.500
I know!

02:08.500 --> 02:10.266
That vanilla latte
is for you

02:10.266 --> 02:12.400
and I wanna hear
everything.

02:12.400 --> 02:13.733
How's Ethan?

02:13.733 --> 02:15.700
Ethan's good.
He's good.

02:15.700 --> 02:18.566
We kind of had this weird thing
happen at Sam's birthday.

02:18.566 --> 02:21.766
But it's, I mean,
ugh, sorry.

02:21.766 --> 02:24.600
Sorry, it's that time again.

02:24.600 --> 02:28.433
It's always that time,
yes, yes.

02:28.433 --> 02:30.433
So now he's in Montreal
for a stag

02:30.433 --> 02:32.033
and of course,
his ex-wife is there.

02:32.033 --> 02:33.300
So, I'm thinking...

02:33.300 --> 02:35.133
So, no, you keep obsessing
over things

02:35.133 --> 02:37.200
that aren't actually
happening.

02:37.200 --> 02:39.433
Well, I guess
you could put it that way.

02:39.433 --> 02:40.500
Alyson:
Judith, Jude!

02:40.500 --> 02:41.333
Hi guys!

02:41.333 --> 02:42.266
Alyson:
Erica, right?

02:42.266 --> 02:44.166
You mind if we join you?

02:44.166 --> 02:47.000
Chaz is out cold and we're,
like, insanely early for yoga.

02:47.000 --> 02:48.033
Mm-hmm.

02:48.033 --> 02:50.533
Alyson:
Oops, okay there?

02:50.533 --> 02:52.566
Marie: Oh, wow, his
feet are freezing.

02:52.566 --> 02:57.000
Judith:
Oh, I've got a blanket.

02:57.000 --> 02:58.566
I don't think that
I'm obsessing.

02:58.566 --> 03:00.633
Oh, sorry
if that came off harsh,

03:00.633 --> 03:02.500
I'm just a little
out of practice.

03:02.500 --> 03:04.600
No, it's fine, I mean,
I want your opinion.

03:04.600 --> 03:05.666
No, no, no!

03:06.666 --> 03:08.633
Oh, do not bite mommy.

03:08.633 --> 03:10.333
When you bite mommy
it hurts.

03:10.333 --> 03:11.700
Alyson: See, what
I don't understand

03:11.700 --> 03:13.733
is why people are just not
born with teeth?

03:13.733 --> 03:14.566
Exactly!

03:14.566 --> 03:15.633
Isn't that what I said?

03:15.633 --> 03:17.700
Oh my god,
I just talked about this.

03:17.700 --> 03:19.200
Judith: It's like gnawing away.

03:19.200 --> 03:20.700
Judith: Is he still biting you?

03:20.700 --> 03:23.533
Marie: Yeah.
Judith: Wow, you poor thing.

03:23.533 --> 03:24.400
Are you pacifying?

03:24.400 --> 03:25.500
Marie: Yes.

03:25.500 --> 03:28.033
Marie's mother
is completely pro-pacifier.

03:28.033 --> 03:32.266
Ah, so that makes her
a pacifist.

03:32.266 --> 03:33.700
Judith: Look, it's a
personal decision.

03:33.700 --> 03:35.666
I just believe babies
need an opportunity

03:35.666 --> 03:37.266
to practice self
soothing, you know?

03:37.266 --> 03:39.233
Pacifiers are unhygienic,
disgusting pieces of plastic.

03:39.233 --> 03:40.633
Alyson: See, I told you.

03:40.633 --> 03:42.200
Marie: I don't know
about that.

03:42.200 --> 03:44.366
Alyson: No, we've been having
this discussion all week.

03:44.366 --> 03:45.633
Judith: Really?
Alyson: Yeah.

03:45.633 --> 03:46.700
Alyson: I'm
onboard with you.

03:46.700 --> 03:48.266
(clears throat)

03:49.566 --> 03:51.666
Vegan nanaimo bar?

03:51.666 --> 03:53.666
Mmm, just a water.

03:53.666 --> 03:55.733
Just an excuse,
actually.

03:55.733 --> 03:56.633
Tired?

03:56.633 --> 03:58.033
Yup.

03:58.033 --> 04:00.100
Just got back from 92
the other day.

04:00.100 --> 04:01.566
The air was cleaner there.

04:01.566 --> 04:05.266
It's a real adjustment.

04:05.266 --> 04:08.400
Wow, you really don't wanna
talk about the therapy, do you?

04:11.066 --> 04:13.433
Let's talk about your friend,
the one who's ignoring you.

04:13.433 --> 04:15.533
Yeah, that's my
best friend.

04:15.533 --> 04:18.399
And she used to be
terrified of kids.

04:18.399 --> 04:21.399
Ah, things change,
apparently.

04:21.399 --> 04:23.200
Yup, but I mean,
it's good.

04:23.200 --> 04:24.600
I'm happy for her.

04:24.600 --> 04:26.133
(smug laugh)

04:26.133 --> 04:27.533
Yeah, right.

04:27.533 --> 04:29.066
What? I am.

04:29.066 --> 04:32.233
No, you're not
and I don't blame you.

04:32.233 --> 04:34.300
Kids come along,
people forget who they are.

04:34.300 --> 04:36.066
Their friends.

04:36.066 --> 04:37.700
A lot of marriages
don't survive kids,

04:37.700 --> 04:39.400
I bet even more
friendships don't.

04:39.400 --> 04:41.700
Oh really,
and how would you know?

04:41.700 --> 04:45.066
You look like you're
barely out of high school.

04:45.066 --> 04:47.000
Thanks for the water.

04:47.000 --> 04:48.233
Friendships
like everything else,

04:48.233 --> 04:50.233
are not immune to change.

04:50.233 --> 04:51.566
The question is:

04:51.566 --> 04:53.766
How do you keep
a friendship together

04:53.766 --> 04:55.733
when your lives
are pulling you apart?

04:55.733 --> 04:58.566
♪

05:05.566 --> 05:08.433
♪ It's clearer inside of me ♪

05:08.433 --> 05:11.166
♪ Who I will always be ♪

05:11.166 --> 05:13.233
♪ Open me up to my heart ♪

05:16.133 --> 05:18.566
♪ Feels like I'm seeing
in the dark ♪

05:18.566 --> 05:20.766
♪ Waking me up to my heart ♪

05:20.766 --> 05:23.300
♪ To do it all over... ♪

05:23.300 --> 05:26.133
♪ Again and again ♪

05:26.133 --> 05:28.433
♪ Until the end ♪

05:28.433 --> 05:30.766
♪ The sum of my dreams ♪

05:30.766 --> 05:34.500
♪ And everything
I ever wanted to be ♪

05:36.333 --> 05:38.700
Judith: Oh, sorry if I got
sucked into the whole mom vortex

05:38.700 --> 05:39.766
back there.

05:39.766 --> 05:41.300
It's okay.

05:41.300 --> 05:42.633
You were telling me
about Ethan?

05:42.633 --> 05:44.366
Yeah, it's just
all the little things

05:44.366 --> 05:46.066
that are starting to add up.

05:46.066 --> 05:47.366
Yeah,
tell me about it.

05:47.366 --> 05:50.133
Like when I'm trying to remind
Anthony to bring the diaper bag

05:50.133 --> 05:50.766
every single day.

05:50.766 --> 05:52.033
Uh, I guess...

05:52.033 --> 05:53.166
(cell phone rings)

05:53.166 --> 05:54.500
Oh, just a sec.

05:54.500 --> 05:56.466
Hey,
ch-ch-ch-ch-ch.

05:56.466 --> 05:58.033
What's up, hon?

05:58.033 --> 05:59.533
Well, my mom has a cold.

05:59.533 --> 06:01.533
She said she could
still make it though.

06:01.533 --> 06:04.033
No, uh, I don't want her
taking care of him

06:04.033 --> 06:05.433
if she's sick.

06:07.400 --> 06:09.633
I guess you could
stay home.

06:09.633 --> 06:13.366
No, I don't wanna
stay home. um...

06:13.366 --> 06:15.400
I'll figure it out, okay?

06:15.400 --> 06:17.466
Anthony:
I'm sorry, all right?

06:17.466 --> 06:19.066
See you tonight.

06:19.066 --> 06:20.733
What's going on?

06:20.733 --> 06:23.666
Oh, Anthony's giving a speech
at this diversity dinner

06:23.666 --> 06:26.566
for the bank in, like,
ooh, four hours?

06:26.566 --> 06:29.033
And I just lost the only
baby-sitter that I trust.

06:29.033 --> 06:30.700
Oh.

06:30.700 --> 06:33.400
Well,
why don't I just do it?

06:35.033 --> 06:36.566
Well...

06:36.566 --> 06:39.366
It's sweet of you to offer,
it's just that he's teething

06:39.366 --> 06:41.066
and being really difficult.

06:41.066 --> 06:43.533
Jude, I used to baby-sit
all the time.

06:43.533 --> 06:44.600
I can handle it.

06:46.100 --> 06:48.233
Unless you don't...

06:48.233 --> 06:49.633
I mean,
unless you don't trust me?

06:49.633 --> 06:50.700
No.

06:50.700 --> 06:52.266
No, it's not that.

06:52.266 --> 06:55.100
I just, I'm really precise
about his schedule.

06:55.100 --> 06:56.366
Oh, I know schedules,
lady.

06:56.366 --> 07:00.300
I've been taking the bus
since 1987.

07:00.300 --> 07:02.066
Can you make it for 6:30?

07:02.066 --> 07:04.300
I can be early
'cause I'm that good.

07:04.300 --> 07:06.566
You're awesome.

07:06.566 --> 07:07.300
Thank you.

07:10.400 --> 07:11.733
Really?

07:11.733 --> 07:14.566
How old is little Max,
Erica?

07:14.566 --> 07:17.266
Why will no one believe that
I'm an amazing baby-sitter?

07:17.266 --> 07:19.233
I used to baby-sit Sam.

07:19.233 --> 07:21.533
She was 8-years-old, honey.
Max is a baby.

07:21.533 --> 07:23.333
But I'm sure you'll do fine.

07:23.333 --> 07:25.433
Mmm,
very convincing, mom.

07:25.433 --> 07:26.666
(chuckles)

07:26.666 --> 07:28.133
Erica: Listen,
sorry about dinner.

07:28.133 --> 07:30.100
You're sure
it's not a problem?

07:30.100 --> 07:32.266
Not at all, honey.
I'll call you later.

07:32.266 --> 07:33.233
Erica:
Okay, bye.

07:33.233 --> 07:34.566
Sam:
Hey, mom.

07:34.566 --> 07:35.633
Hey!

07:35.633 --> 07:38.166
Errand day.

07:38.166 --> 07:39.500
Just dropping
your tupperware back.

07:39.500 --> 07:41.166
You could've kept those.
Muah.

07:41.166 --> 07:41.766
Ehn.

07:43.433 --> 07:45.166
What are you doing
for dinner tonight?

07:45.166 --> 07:46.166
Josh was gonna barbecue.

07:46.166 --> 07:47.266
Tell him to barbecue
tomorrow;

07:47.266 --> 07:49.466
I have an entire lasagna.

07:49.466 --> 07:52.633
We kinda have
a lot to do at home.

07:52.633 --> 07:54.500
So, we take the lasagna
to your house

07:54.500 --> 07:56.233
and maybe I can help out.

07:56.233 --> 07:58.033
Okay.

07:58.033 --> 07:59.400
I wasn't gonna say
anything yet,

07:59.400 --> 08:03.133
but we're moving
to London.

08:03.133 --> 08:06.200
Head office offered him
senior vp.

08:07.266 --> 08:08.633
Oh.

08:08.633 --> 08:09.733
Oh, Sam.

08:11.033 --> 08:12.533
London, England?

08:12.533 --> 08:15.066
This is good news, mom.

08:15.066 --> 08:17.166
Of course it is.

08:17.166 --> 08:19.400
It's just such a change.

08:21.066 --> 08:23.000
Oh, um...

08:23.000 --> 08:25.400
Well, what about your work?

08:25.400 --> 08:27.300
Well, they have hospitals
in London,

08:27.300 --> 08:29.033
and there are worse things

08:29.033 --> 08:31.466
than getting European
certification,

08:31.466 --> 08:33.633
and a couple of years
of overseas experience...

08:33.633 --> 08:36.233
A couple of years?

08:36.233 --> 08:38.299
Don't act all judgey
and Erica,

08:38.299 --> 08:40.666
and just be happy for us.

08:43.000 --> 08:45.500
Listen,
if this is what you want

08:45.500 --> 08:49.466
then of course I'm happy
for you, sweetheart.

08:49.466 --> 08:51.400
It's what we want.

08:57.000 --> 08:59.266
go in the microwave,

08:59.266 --> 09:00.266
it destroys the enzymes.

09:00.266 --> 09:02.266
Anthony: You waste
a drop of that stuff

09:02.266 --> 09:03.333
and she'll come
after you.

09:03.333 --> 09:05.333
Hi.

09:05.333 --> 09:07.100
I am all over it.

09:07.100 --> 09:09.466
Breast milk goes in warm water
until it's body temperature.

09:09.466 --> 09:11.000
That's impressive.
Thank you.

09:11.000 --> 09:13.500
I did research.
I'm prepared.

09:13.500 --> 09:15.733
Okay, bedtime is at seven
on the dot.

09:15.733 --> 09:17.733
Otherwise he gets overtired.

09:17.733 --> 09:19.466
Erica,
just keep him alive,

09:19.466 --> 09:21.066
everything else
is details, okay.

09:21.066 --> 09:22.066
I'm not joking, okay?

09:22.066 --> 09:24.300
If he gets tired,
he'll just rub his eyes

09:24.300 --> 09:26.066
and fuss so much
he can't sleep.

09:26.066 --> 09:27.600
Erica:
No, I know, I got it.

09:27.600 --> 09:28.700
Judith: Do you?

09:28.700 --> 09:31.066
Well, because if you don't,
he'll be off for days.

09:31.066 --> 09:32.366
And this matters
because it's just...

09:32.366 --> 09:33.433
Loud and clear, Judith.

09:33.433 --> 09:34.566
(car honks outside)

09:34.566 --> 09:36.100
There's the cab,
yup, gotta go, babe.

09:36.100 --> 09:37.366
Okay, um...

09:37.366 --> 09:39.566
Once you put him down,
do not pick him up, okay?

09:39.566 --> 09:41.400
I'm teaching him to self-soothe
without any props.

09:41.400 --> 09:42.633
Or no pacifiers,

09:42.633 --> 09:44.600
no rocking him to sleep
or anything like that.

09:44.600 --> 09:46.066
Okay, Judith,
research also says

09:46.066 --> 09:48.766
that at a certain point,
you have to stop being a mom

09:48.766 --> 09:50.500
and just go have fun.

09:50.500 --> 09:51.333
Judith: Okay.

09:51.333 --> 09:52.200
Anthony: Okay, Erica.

09:52.200 --> 09:53.233
Anthony: Thank you.

09:53.233 --> 09:55.233
Judith: Thanks.

09:55.233 --> 09:56.233
Erica:
Okay, have fun.

09:56.233 --> 09:57.333
(Max fusses)

10:01.233 --> 10:02.600
Crazy Aunt Erica,

10:02.600 --> 10:05.533
She's smarter
than your mommy thinks.

10:05.533 --> 10:07.266
Yes, she is.

10:07.266 --> 10:09.066
(telephone ringing)

10:09.066 --> 10:10.300
Hello?

10:10.300 --> 10:12.566
Erica: So, I just
called to let you know

10:12.566 --> 10:14.133
that we made it
'till bedtime.

10:14.133 --> 10:16.033
Without a single tear.

10:16.033 --> 10:17.233
Wonderful.

10:17.233 --> 10:18.566
Erica: And can I just
say for the record

10:18.566 --> 10:20.000
that snuggling a
warm baby,

10:20.000 --> 10:22.700
it's hardly the rough job
you mothers make it out to be.

10:22.700 --> 10:24.333
Uh-huh.

10:24.333 --> 10:26.400
So, Sam came over
and ate your lasagna.

10:26.400 --> 10:27.233
Is that Erica?

10:27.233 --> 10:28.633
Yes.

10:28.633 --> 10:30.333
Oh, Sam, sweetheart, can you
go downstairs to the basement

10:30.333 --> 10:31.633
and get some more
paper towel?

10:31.633 --> 10:34.100
Sam: Mhm.
Barbara: Thank you.

10:36.666 --> 10:39.500
They're moving to London.

10:39.500 --> 10:40.433
What, really?

10:40.433 --> 10:42.466
Sam?

10:42.466 --> 10:45.333
I mean, she could hardly
handle going to camp.

10:45.333 --> 10:47.766
Wow.
Well, good for her.

10:47.766 --> 10:50.266
Mm, it's for Josh,
a promotion.

10:50.266 --> 10:52.433
Ah, big surprise.

10:52.433 --> 10:55.066
She's acting excited,
but...

10:55.066 --> 10:57.233
I don't think
she's that into it.

10:57.233 --> 10:58.600
Uh, well,
then talk to her.

10:58.600 --> 11:00.600
I mean, mom,
if you're worried?

11:00.600 --> 11:02.633
Oh, you know how
defensive Sam can get.

11:02.633 --> 11:03.466
Do I...

11:03.466 --> 11:05.600
Shh-shh-shh.

11:05.600 --> 11:07.700
This is the thing,
you are her mother

11:07.700 --> 11:10.500
and your real opinion,
it matters to her.

11:10.500 --> 11:12.366
If you think this
is the wrong decision

11:12.366 --> 11:15.466
then you need
to speak up.

11:15.466 --> 11:16.500
Oh, oh, oh...

11:16.500 --> 11:19.066
Mom, it's Max's bedtime,
I gotta go.

11:19.066 --> 11:21.300
Of course, sweetheart,
I'll call you later, okay?

11:21.300 --> 11:22.733
Okay, bye.

11:22.733 --> 11:23.700
Say, bye.

11:25.333 --> 11:26.500
(telephone beeps off)

11:28.000 --> 11:30.166
It's time for bed.

11:30.166 --> 11:33.000
It's time for bed,
yes, sir, mister.

11:33.000 --> 11:35.333
Mmmm...

11:35.333 --> 11:37.033
(gasps)

11:37.033 --> 11:37.600
There you go.

11:39.266 --> 11:40.633
Don't tell mom it's
7:10, okay?

11:40.633 --> 11:43.500
That's between you and I.

11:43.500 --> 11:45.200
Good nightie-night
night-night-night.

11:45.200 --> 11:46.566
(Max fusses and cries)

11:50.300 --> 11:51.433
(Max cries)

11:58.033 --> 12:00.000
No, Erica.

12:01.500 --> 12:02.566
(sympathetic groan)

